ere is a 'Jewish question' that needs to be 'solved'. This original and stimulating book traces struggles within the Enlightenment, Marxism, critical theory and the contemporary left, seeking to rescue universalism from its repressive, antisemitic undertones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntisemitism. 0aUniversalism. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aChristian von Dohm.  aHabermas.  aIsrael.  aJewish emancipation.  aMoses Mendelssohn.  aThe Jewish Question.  aUniversalism.  aZionism.  aanti-Semitism.  aassimilationism.  acosmopolitanism.  aparticularism.1 aFine, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpencer, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSpencer, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526104960zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526104960zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526104960/original  a978-3-11-128281-7 Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA